{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c567a2e-650f-48cb-a352-3de7fd69e6b9","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class span types** in overload resolution. `int[]` is now implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, and the compiler prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` over the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`.\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees — so the tree either fails to compile or fails at runtime when the interpreter encounters the span-based method.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler selects the LINQ overload again:\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: cast the array to IEnumerable<int>\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option B: call Enumerable.Contains explicitly\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither form forces resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees can represent and the interpreter can execute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0984d022-ffe0-4a8f-9caa-6037a92a7e7b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to **extension members** and how the compiler resolves extension methods. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension types** (the new `extension` keyword), but more relevantly, there's a breaking change related to how `Enumerable.Contains()` is resolved.\n \nIn .NET 9, `int[].Contains(int)` resolves to the LINQ extension method `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>()`, but in .NET 10 there's likely a new overload or method resolu